<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>This was revealed by Transport MEC Mxolisi Kaunda at a road safety march and prayer session.It was held at Matiwane, outside Ladysmith in northern KZN, on Sunday.Spokesman Mluleki Mntungwa told the People’s Paper: “We are very optimistic that people will be safe on the roads this Easter holiday.” He asked road users to respect road rules to avoid unnecessary deaths. “The 27 000 cops began working on 15 March and will continue until 10 April,” he said. “We are hopeful that everything will go well.” Mntungwa said the cops had been briefed to target hot spots such as the borders linking KZN to other provinces and neighbouring countries.“At such borders we will be working with cops and law enforcement agencies from the respective provinces and neighbouring countries such as Mozambique, Lesotho and Swaziland,” said Mntungwa.Thabisile Mngomezulu (38), a resident of Ladysmith, will be travelling to Durban for a Good Friday service.She said she was putting all her hopes and trust in the traffic cops.“Cops give us hope when they stop and check the buses and taxis we travel in,” said Thabisile. “It’s very sad that people have died on the roads because we are driven by drunk drivers whose vehicles are not even roadworthy.”